Overview

This document captures the security vulnerabilities identified in the Fragments collaborative storytelling platform during the investigation phase. The issues are interconnected across authentication and authorization layers, leading to privilege escalation, broken access control, and session misuse.

1. Hardcoded JWT Secret & No Expiry
Issue
The JWT secret is hardcoded in server/auth/jwt.js.
Tokens are signed without an expiry (expiresIn).
Impact
Anyone with access to the source code can generate valid tokens.
Stolen tokens remain valid indefinitely.
No way to enforce session expiration → long-term account compromise.
Evidence
Found string literal used as JWT secret.
Tokens remain valid even after long periods.
2. Role Missing from JWT Payload
Issue
The JWT payload (in server/routes/auth.js) does not include user role.
Impact
Backend cannot reliably determine user permissions.
Role-based access control becomes ineffective.
Opens path for privilege escalation when combined with frontend manipulation.
Evidence
Decoded JWT only contains user ID/email, no role field.
3. Frontend Stores Role in localStorage
Issue
User role is stored in localStorage (AuthContext.jsx).
Impact
Role can be manually modified via browser DevTools.
UI updates to reflect elevated permissions (e.g., admin buttons visible).
Creates a false sense of authorization enforcement.
Exploit Demonstration
Changed role from reader → admin in DevTools.
Admin UI controls appeared without backend validation.
4. Missing Role Checks on Critical Endpoints
Issue

Endpoints in server/routes/fragments.js lack proper role validation:

POST /api/fragments
PUT /api/fragments/:id
POST /api/fragments/:id/approve
DELETE /api/fragments/:id
Impact
Any authenticated user can perform restricted actions.
Users can:
Approve content without curator role
Delete fragments without admin rights
Edit others’ content
Root Cause
Either:
No role checks exist, OR
Role checks fail due to missing role in JWT
5. CSRF Vulnerability
Issue
CORS policy is overly permissive (server/index.js).
No CSRF protection implemented for state-changing requests.
Impact
Malicious websites can send authenticated requests using victim’s session.
Leads to:
Unauthorized fragment creation
Forced approvals or deletions
Evidence
Requests succeed without CSRF tokens.
No origin restriction enforced.
6. Logout Does Not Invalidate Token
Issue
Logout only removes token from localStorage (LogoutButton.jsx).
Token remains valid on the server.
Impact
Stolen/copied tokens can still be used after logout.
No server-side session invalidation.
Exploit Demonstration
Copied JWT before logout.
Used it in Postman after logout → still authenticated successfully.
Interconnection of Issues

These vulnerabilities are not isolated:

Missing role in JWT + role stored in localStorage → easy privilege escalation
No role checks + manipulated role → full access to protected actions
Hardcoded secret + no expiry → persistent unauthorized access
No CSRF protection → attackers can exploit active sessions
No logout invalidation → compromised tokens remain usable

Together, they create a completely broken access control system.

Summary

The application suffers from:

Broken authentication (JWT mismanagement)
Broken authorization (missing role enforcement)
Client-side trust issues (localStorage role)
Session security flaws (no expiry, no invalidation)
Cross-site attack exposure (CSRF)

These combined flaws allow attackers to:

Escalate privileges
Perform unauthorized actions
Maintain persistent access
